@page "/admin/subditem"
@layout STTproject.Shared.Layout.Admin.AdminSideBar

<h3>SubdItem</h3>
@* The straightforward, low-risk version of this: a pricelist page that lists items with their current price (pulling from ItemsUoms/SubdItem much like GetMapSubDistributorItemsAsync already does), lets the admin edit prices inline or in a modal, and saves through the same SaveSubdItemUomPricesAsync you already have — meaning it inherits the history-logging behavior for free. No new invoice-related code needed at all; you're just giving admins a more convenient surface for something the system already supports.
A few things worth adding while you're building it, since they fit naturally:
Since you're now actually populating ItemsUomPriceHistory, this page is a good place to surface it — an expandable row or a small "price history" panel per item showing past changes (old price, new price, when it took effect), pulled straight from that table. That gives admins visibility into when and why a price moved, which is useful on its own and also makes the "this doesn't touch past invoices" behavior more transparent, since they can literally see the timeline.
On the UI itself, I'd put a small, persistent note near the price-edit control — something like "price changes apply to new invoices going forward; existing invoices are not affected" — so it's explicit rather than something admins have to intuit. That single sentence prevents the exact misunderstanding we just untangled, where someone assumes editing a price here will retroactively fix invoices.
For validation, since this page will probably be used more casually than the Map Item screen (a quick "update this item's price" workflow rather than a full item edit), it's worth double-checking your existing oldPrice != newPrice comparison handles decimal precision sensibly — e.g. if the UI rounds displayed prices to 2 decimals but the underlying value has more precision, you don't want spurious history rows logging a "change" from 100.001 to 100.00 that the admin never actually intended.
What I'd explicitly leave out, at least for now: any button or flow that says "apply this new price to existing invoices." If that need comes up later — a genuine, audited correction to invoices already issued — build it as its own deliberate feature with its own confirmation step and audit trail, separate from this page, rather than bolting it onto the pricelist editor as a checkbox. 
